00:01:46.910 --> 00:01:49.460
And he defined as the
'fundamental axiom' of his

00:01:49.460 --> 00:01:52.027
philosophy the principle that
'it is the greatest happiness

00:01:52.027 --> 00:01:54.110
of the greatest number
that's the measure of right

00:01:54.110 --> 00:01:57.140
and wrong.'" And so this sort
of hedonic or philosophic

00:01:57.140 --> 00:02:00.860
calculus, which Bentham
called it, happiness maths,

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:04.130
is basically a kind of cost
benefit analysis using pleasure

00:02:04.130 --> 00:02:05.310
and pain.

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:07.723
So when you're trying to figure
out what action is right,

00:02:07.723 --> 00:02:10.139
you should consider the pleasure
and the pains that result

00:02:10.139 --> 00:02:13.520
from it, and how intense
they are, how long they last,

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:15.200
how certain you are
of them, how near

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:16.770
they are at hand,
how likely they

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:18.680
are to lead to future
pleasures and pains,

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:21.417
and how many people they
benefit or they hurt.

00:02:21.417 --> 00:02:23.500
And then you should consider
all the alternatives.

00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:27.380
And that might be the best
way to choose what to do.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:30.632
Now, around 100 years after
Bentham, we have Edgeworth.

00:02:30.632 --> 00:02:32.840
He was the founding editor
of "The Economic Journal,"

00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:35.256
and laid lots of the foundations
of sort of modern utility

00:02:35.256 --> 00:02:35.760
theory.

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:37.801
And Edgeworth went as far
as to imagine something

00:02:37.801 --> 00:02:42.770
that he called a hedonometer,
an idealized happiness measuring

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:44.300
machine.

00:02:44.300 --> 00:02:45.920
And he waxed really
lyrical about this

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:48.770
and says "let there be granted
to the science of pleasure what

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:50.700
is granted to the
science of energy.

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:52.400
Imagine an ideally
perfect instrument,

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:55.250
a psychophysical machine,
continually registering

00:02:55.250 --> 00:02:58.400
the heights of pleasure
experienced by an individual,

00:02:58.400 --> 00:03:00.650
exactly according to the
verdict of consciousness

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:03.800
or rather diverging there from,
according to a law of errors.

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:06.440
From moment to moment,
the hedonometer varies,

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:07.850
the delicate index
now flickering

00:03:07.850 --> 00:03:09.770
with the flutter of the
passions, now steadied

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:12.140
by intellectual
activity, low sunk

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:13.860
whole hours in the
neighborhood of zero,

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:17.300
will momentarily spring
up towards infinity."

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:19.190
But unfortunately,
Edgeworth's peers

00:03:19.190 --> 00:03:22.040
were mostly not on
board with this idea.

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:24.560
Economists then, in
the early 20th century,

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:27.320
increasingly wanted to be
thought of as scientists.

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:29.000
They had a kind of physics envy.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:30.541
And they certainly
did not want to be

00:03:30.541 --> 00:03:35.060
thought of as psychologists
such as Freud, who we see here.

00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:38.670
And therefore, if we look at
Pareto, Pareto, for example,

00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:40.430
was very proud of
his Theory of Choice

00:03:40.430 --> 00:03:42.890
in which he said that every
psychological analysis is

00:03:42.890 --> 00:03:43.880
eliminated.

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:46.190
And he boasts that he's not
interested in the reason

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:48.380
why man is indifferent
between one bundle of goods

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:49.620
and another bundle of goods.

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:52.160
"I notice the pure
and naked fact."

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:55.610
And so words like willpower
and imagination and feelings

00:03:55.610 --> 00:03:57.834
began to vanish from economics.

00:03:57.834 --> 00:04:00.500
Instead, economists came up with
very elegant and certainly very

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:03.560
useful theories of well-being
as preference satisfaction,

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:05.870
where you're happy to the
extent that you can satisfy

00:04:05.870 --> 00:04:08.660
your consumer preferences, and
you can approximate the extent

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:10.940
that you can satisfy you
consumer preferences by how

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:12.110
much income you have.

00:04:12.110 --> 00:04:13.580
And therefore the
recommendations

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:15.717
of economists tended towards--

00:04:15.717 --> 00:04:17.300
both for individuals
and for nations--

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:20.600
well, do your best
to get richer.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:22.490
Now, 20th century
economists were not stupid.

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:23.540
And of course,
they're not oblivious

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:25.730
to the potential unintended
consequences of that.

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:28.215
But they have this
special powerful Latin

00:04:28.215 --> 00:04:29.840
to protect their
assumptions from that.

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:31.610
So we just say
"ceteris paribus,"

00:04:31.610 --> 00:04:32.990
and that means all other
things being equal--

00:04:32.990 --> 00:04:34.160
and definitely it's true--

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:37.010
but all other things being
equal, aiming to get richer

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:39.850
is a pretty solid idea.

00:04:39.850 --> 00:04:42.320
But around the 1970s,
some economists

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:44.840
started asking awkward
questions on this topic.

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:47.020
And in particular, here
is Richard Easterlin

00:04:47.020 --> 00:04:48.420
of the University
of Pennsylvania

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:50.340
and now the University
of Southern California,

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:52.423
who's commonly regarded
as sort of the grandfather

00:04:52.423 --> 00:04:54.410
of modern happiness economics.

00:04:54.410 --> 00:04:57.740
And Easterlin published a
paper in 1974 with the title

00:04:57.740 --> 00:05:01.430
"Does Economic Growth
Improve the Human Lot?"

00:05:01.430 --> 00:05:03.650
which was probably the
economists' equivalent of

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:05.380
is the pope Catholic
and do bears

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:07.350
go to the toilet in the woods?

00:05:07.350 --> 00:05:09.220
But Easterlin was
sort of looking

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:11.380
to confront this
economic growth data

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:13.820
with some kind of external
measure of happiness.

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:18.040
And in order to do that, he used
self-reported well-being survey

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:18.930
data.

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:21.150
And following Easterlin,
lots of other economists

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:22.740
have taken up this
line of thinking.

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:25.090
And one of the key figures,
certainly, in this country

00:05:25.090 --> 00:05:28.882
is Professor Richard Layard,
who is a labor economist at LSC

00:05:28.882 --> 00:05:30.340
and a member of
the House of Lords.

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:32.530
Layard wrote an
influential book in 2005

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.270
based on some
earlier lectures, and

00:05:34.270 --> 00:05:37.172
along with the former cabinet
secretary here, Gus O'Donnell,

00:05:37.172 --> 00:05:39.130
has been kind of instrumental
in getting the UK

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:41.171
government to take well-being
measures seriously,

00:05:41.171 --> 00:05:46.060
both within the civil service
and in the country at large.

00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:48.880
I said Easterlin used
self-reported well-being survey

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:49.540
data.

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:50.590
What is that data?

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:52.341
Well, it's answers to
questions like this.

00:05:52.341 --> 00:05:54.090
And actually, these
are the four questions

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:55.870
that the Office for
National Statistics

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:58.900
now asks regularly
across the country

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:00.520
of a representative sample.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:03.135
How satisfied are you
with your life nowadays?

00:06:03.135 --> 00:06:04.510
And this relates
to what we often

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:06.580
call the evaluative
account of well-being,

00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:09.310
thinking about your
life as a whole.

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:11.860
It asks what extent do
you feel the things you

00:06:11.860 --> 00:06:13.830
do in your life are worthwhile?

00:06:13.830 --> 00:06:16.960
And that gets at what we often
call the eudemonic account

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:19.330
of well-being, sense of
meaning, sense of purpose,

00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:22.330
sense that what you do in
your life is worthwhile.

00:06:22.330 --> 00:06:23.890
And then the last
two questions, how

00:06:23.890 --> 00:06:25.570
happy did you feel
yesterday and how

00:06:25.570 --> 00:06:27.260
anxious did you
feel yesterday, get

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:29.290
at what we call the
hedonic account, which

00:06:29.290 --> 00:06:33.100
goes back to Aristotle, as in
fact the eudemonic account does

00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:34.676
too.

00:06:34.676 --> 00:06:36.550
That's sometimes sort
of rather deprecatingly

00:06:36.550 --> 00:06:38.200
referred to as
smiley face feeling.

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:41.440
It's kind of mood,
emotion, in the moment,

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.900
the most immediate kind
of measure of happiness.

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:45.130
Now, all three of these
accounts of well-being

00:06:45.130 --> 00:06:46.150
are very highly correlated.

00:06:46.150 --> 00:06:47.566
You know, you'd
expect that people

00:06:47.566 --> 00:06:50.330
who have enjoyable moments feel
satisfied with their lives,

00:06:50.330 --> 00:06:53.680
for example, although there are
some interesting divergences.

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:56.320
Having kids might cause you to
have an interesting divergence

00:06:56.320 --> 00:06:57.028
in some of these.

00:06:57.028 --> 00:06:59.922
You might get very high highs
but also some fairly low lows.

00:06:59.922 --> 00:07:01.880
You might feel that your
life has more purpose.

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:03.730
It might affect
things differently.

00:07:03.730 --> 00:07:05.480
By and large they move
together, but there

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:07.954
are some things that can move
them somewhat separately.

00:07:07.954 --> 00:07:09.370
Economists have
mostly just looked

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:10.630
at the evaluative
account, because it's

00:07:10.630 --> 00:07:11.796
really easy to get ahold of.

00:07:11.796 --> 00:07:13.769
It's one question, and
you can ask it today,

00:07:13.769 --> 00:07:15.560
and you can ask it next
week and next month

00:07:15.560 --> 00:07:16.470
and you'll get a similar answer.

00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:18.470
So you can sort of
shove it into any survey

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:20.292
that you're asking people.

00:07:20.292 --> 00:07:22.000
And it's also the one
that's most closely

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.880
related to people's income,
which makes economists

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:26.290
feel comfortable with it.

00:07:26.290 --> 00:07:28.030
My own project,
Mappiness, is actually

00:07:28.030 --> 00:07:29.851
primarily a hedonic
measure of happiness.

00:07:29.851 --> 00:07:31.600
And not just how happy
you felt yesterday,

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:33.860
but how happy do
you feel right now.

00:07:33.860 --> 00:07:36.820
And I will talk a whole
lot more about that soon.

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:39.520
A key question that comes up
in economics and elsewhere

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:40.270
is very simple.

00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:41.080
Is this valid?

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:42.400
Is this meaningful?

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:44.710
Can people really reduce
the quality of their life

00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:46.061
to 0 to 10 scale?

00:07:46.061 --> 00:07:47.560
And certainly within
economics there

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:49.807
remains an amount of
controversy about this.

00:07:49.807 --> 00:07:51.640
There are certainly
economists who are quite

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:54.280
wedded to the preference
satisfaction view,

00:07:54.280 --> 00:07:56.230
and to their indifference
curves, and to not

00:07:56.230 --> 00:08:00.290
getting involved in the messy
business of how people feel.

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:02.830
And in reducing the quality
of your life experience to a 0

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:05.734
to 10 scale, we can certainly
be accused of reductionism.

00:08:05.734 --> 00:08:07.400
It is a kind of
reductionist enterprise.

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:09.460
And I'm not for a minute
saying that's the only way

00:08:09.460 --> 00:08:11.418
that we should seek to
understand people's life

00:08:11.418 --> 00:08:12.089
experiences.

00:08:12.089 --> 00:08:14.380
But my view is certainly that
the subjective well-being

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:16.600
ratings are valid enough
and meaningful enough

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:18.550
to tell us interesting
and valuable things.

00:08:18.550 --> 00:08:21.610
And for one thing, there's
a lot of convergeability.

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:24.820
Lots of other things point
very much in the same way.

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:27.270
For example, subjective
well-being responses

00:08:27.270 --> 00:08:29.870
are very strongly correlated
with objective indicators,

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:33.850
including neural
activity from fMRI scans.

00:08:33.850 --> 00:08:35.440
Biochemical markers,
such as levels

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:39.429
of cortisol in the blood,
heart rate, blood pressure,

00:08:39.429 --> 00:08:43.690
smiling, other people's ratings
of a person's well-being.

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:46.480
They're a strong predictor
of people's future behavior.

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:47.950
And subjective
well-being ratings

00:08:47.950 --> 00:08:51.244
are also very highly
correlated with income.

00:08:51.244 --> 00:08:53.410
Certainly they're very
highly correlated with income

00:08:53.410 --> 00:08:56.439
if you look at a single
country at one time.

00:08:56.439 --> 00:08:58.480
The income relationship
is sort of less clear cut

00:08:58.480 --> 00:09:01.120
if you look between countries.

00:09:01.120 --> 00:09:02.710
And we could talk
about this all day.

00:09:02.710 --> 00:09:03.900
These charts are
sort of interesting.

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:04.960
So these are actually
the same charts.

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:06.500
One of them is on a log scale.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:08.360
One of them is on
a linear scale.

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:10.300
And the choice of which
one of these you plot

00:09:10.300 --> 00:09:13.210
is actually potentially
quite political.

00:09:13.210 --> 00:09:14.680
If you plot this
one, you kind of

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:16.971
make very clear that Robin
Hood was doing a good thing,

00:09:16.971 --> 00:09:19.084
because up here,
very little happiness

00:09:19.084 --> 00:09:20.500
distinction between
people earning

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:21.860
$100,000 versus $150,000.

00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:24.910
Down here a very large happiness
distinction between people

00:09:24.910 --> 00:09:26.765
with a much smaller
differential.

00:09:26.765 --> 00:09:29.140
So if you ever look at the
Institute for Economic Affairs

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:31.240
report, for example, they'll
always plot this one.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:33.511
But there is a strong
relationship within a country.

00:09:33.511 --> 00:09:35.260
Now, you do need to
be careful when you're

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:36.555
comparing between individuals.

00:09:36.555 --> 00:09:37.930
And certainly you
need to careful

00:09:37.930 --> 00:09:40.610
when you're comparing
values between countries.

00:09:40.610 --> 00:09:42.360
But you can get a lot
of mileage even out

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:45.440
of just the changes within each
individual's own responses.

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:49.930
And that's actually primarily
what my research relies on.

00:09:49.930 --> 00:09:51.610
So I would certainly
argue that this

00:09:51.610 --> 00:09:55.992
is a valid and a useful
way to look at the world.

00:09:55.992 --> 00:09:57.700
Some of you may be
saying, back up a bit,

00:09:57.700 --> 00:09:59.830
didn't I see an fMRI
scan a few slides ago?

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:03.160
Wouldn't that be the gold
standard scientific way

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:04.090
to measure happiness?

00:10:04.090 --> 00:10:06.610
You know, it's got big
machines, costs lots of money,

00:10:06.610 --> 00:10:08.110
spits out hard numbers.

00:10:08.110 --> 00:10:10.420
Give me a break from this
hand-wavy social sciencey

00:10:10.420 --> 00:10:12.430
question asking stuff.

00:10:12.430 --> 00:10:13.210
But actually, no.

00:10:13.210 --> 00:10:14.890
Because happiness
is fundamentally

00:10:14.890 --> 00:10:16.660
a completely subjective thing.

00:10:16.660 --> 00:10:18.710
It's part of an
individual's experience.

00:10:18.710 --> 00:10:21.122
The only reason that we know
what the fMRI scans mean

00:10:21.122 --> 00:10:23.080
and we can interpret them
in terms of happiness

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:24.680
is because at some
point in the past,

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:26.680
we put people in fMRI
machines and we asked them

00:10:26.680 --> 00:10:28.930
how happy they were while we
were scanning their brains.

00:10:28.930 --> 00:10:30.280
So you can make
quite a strong case

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:32.113
that actually, the gold
standard for knowing

00:10:32.113 --> 00:10:35.605
how happy people are
is just to ask them.

00:10:35.605 --> 00:10:38.110
You might also remember
that I promised

00:10:38.110 --> 00:10:40.090
that subjective well-being
data could tell us

00:10:40.090 --> 00:10:41.423
valuable and interesting things.

00:10:41.423 --> 00:10:42.946
So what kinds of
things would be?

00:10:42.946 --> 00:10:44.320
Well, there's at
least three ways

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:47.860
that economists might want to
use subjective well-being data.

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:49.750
One of them is very
simply to test and refine

00:10:49.750 --> 00:10:51.050
other economic theory.

00:10:51.050 --> 00:10:54.610
There's this kind of
tautological sense in economics

00:10:54.610 --> 00:10:56.380
that what do people
want is what they do.

00:10:56.380 --> 00:10:57.920
And what they do, well,
it's what they want.

00:10:57.920 --> 00:10:59.170
And you can't really get
out of that very easily

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:00.970
in this kind of revealed
preference, almost

00:11:00.970 --> 00:11:03.370
kind of behaviorist,
way of figuring out what

00:11:03.370 --> 00:11:04.596
people want in their lives.

00:11:04.596 --> 00:11:06.220
But if you can measure
their happiness,

00:11:06.220 --> 00:11:09.160
you can tell if people do
seem to make the choices that

00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:11.210
make them happier, or
whether they systematically

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:12.990
mispredict what's going
to make them happiest.

00:11:12.990 --> 00:11:13.900
And there's lots
of good evidence

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:15.820
that they do
systematically mispredict,

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:17.320
and they don't make
the choices that

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:21.650
would have appeared to make
them happy in retrospect.

00:11:21.650 --> 00:11:23.194
You can discriminate
between models

00:11:23.194 --> 00:11:24.860
that have different
underlying utilities

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:27.790
but look the same in terms
of people's behavior.

00:11:27.790 --> 00:11:29.890
Becker has an idea of
rational addiction, where

00:11:29.890 --> 00:11:31.960
given a certain
set of preferences,

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:34.210
people can rationally
become addicted to drugs.

00:11:34.210 --> 00:11:35.320
It's very difficult
to distinguish

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:37.445
that when you look at
people's behavior from people

00:11:37.445 --> 00:11:39.040
just lacking
self-control and not

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:40.930
being in control of
the choices they make.

00:11:40.930 --> 00:11:42.640
But if you can
observe how they feel,

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:43.720
then you might be
able to discriminate

00:11:43.720 --> 00:11:46.360
which of those is in fact the
explanation for the behavior

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:47.950
that you see.

00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:49.510
And speaking today,
having just been

00:11:49.510 --> 00:11:51.940
to your canteen, situations
where people are happier

00:11:51.940 --> 00:11:53.740
having less choice,
which is sort

00:11:53.740 --> 00:11:56.680
of paradoxical and impossible
in standard economic theory,

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:59.100
because more choice
always kind of less choice

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:00.200
is nested within it.

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:02.400
And more choice must be better.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:05.500
But it's certainly the
case that sometimes there

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:07.060
are situations
where we are happier

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:09.684
having less choice, just one or
two things to choose for lunch.

00:12:09.684 --> 00:12:13.074
Or I was in a situation where
I got taken somewhere flying

00:12:13.074 --> 00:12:14.240
business class at one point.

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:15.477
And it was amazing.

00:12:15.477 --> 00:12:17.810
And then the next time they
offered to pay me the money,

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:19.210
and then I had to make
a choice whether to fly

00:12:19.210 --> 00:12:20.390
business class or not.

00:12:20.390 --> 00:12:22.510
And that cost me an awful lot
of anguish, because the price is

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:23.020
ridiculous.

00:12:23.020 --> 00:12:26.236
And on the other hand,
I kind of enjoyed it.

00:12:26.236 --> 00:12:27.610
So there are
certainly situations

00:12:27.610 --> 00:12:29.260
where we're happy having no
choice, which don't make sense

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:30.093
in normal economics.

00:12:30.093 --> 00:12:33.647
But subjective well-being data
might help you understand them.

00:12:33.647 --> 00:12:35.980
And there are probably more
things than this you can do.

00:12:35.980 --> 00:12:37.860
But the third of the things
I was going to talk about

00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:39.580
are that we can
value things and we

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:41.110
can sense the
importance of things

00:12:41.110 --> 00:12:42.360
that aren't traded in markets.

00:12:42.360 --> 00:12:44.234
And this might be things
that you really just

00:12:44.234 --> 00:12:46.570
couldn't trade in markets
at all, like marriage.

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:47.980
And there is a paper
that finds that marriage

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:50.063
is extraordinarily valuable
if you try and turn it

00:12:50.063 --> 00:12:52.030
into an income equivalent
in terms of people's

00:12:52.030 --> 00:12:53.490
subjective well-being.

00:12:53.490 --> 00:12:55.300
And also, for example,
the environment,

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:58.051
which in certain areas can
be kind of traded in markets.

00:12:58.051 --> 00:12:59.800
And you can at least
ask people to imagine

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:00.992
that it's traded in markets.

00:13:00.992 --> 00:13:02.950
But nevertheless, that
isn't always very strong

00:13:02.950 --> 00:13:05.290
information on how people
do value the environment

00:13:05.290 --> 00:13:07.420
and how it makes them feel.

00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:10.160
And that brings
me to my research.

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:11.680
And this is the
logo for Mappiness,

00:13:11.680 --> 00:13:14.230
which was an iPhone app that
launched in 2010 as part

00:13:14.230 --> 00:13:15.852
of my PhD at LSC.

00:13:15.852 --> 00:13:17.560
And this is, in a
sense, quite a good day

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:19.434
to take stock of this
project, since actually

00:13:19.434 --> 00:13:21.390
the release of iOS
11 yesterday marks

00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:23.890
the moment when Mappiness just
stops working more or less

00:13:23.890 --> 00:13:25.210
everywhere.

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:27.130
The code was written for iOS 3.

00:13:27.130 --> 00:13:29.500
This was pre automatic
reference counting, and pre

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:31.530
almost everything else.

00:13:31.530 --> 00:13:32.330
So the background.

00:13:32.330 --> 00:13:35.692
What Mappiness is for is
looking at the impact--

00:13:35.692 --> 00:13:37.150
was originally,
certainly-- looking

00:13:37.150 --> 00:13:39.970
at the impact of natural
environments on people's

00:13:39.970 --> 00:13:40.930
happiness.

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:41.800
Here's green space.

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:44.190
Same slide, I think, that
was behind all the logos

00:13:44.190 --> 00:13:45.040
at the beginning.

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:48.100
And we can all agree that green
space, hopefully, is nice.

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:49.062
It makes us feel good.

00:13:49.062 --> 00:13:50.770
And I once went to a
geography conference

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:53.410
where no one said anything
else for three days.

00:13:53.410 --> 00:13:55.180
That's fine as far as it goes.

00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:57.820
But it doesn't go all that
far, because what is actually

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:00.294
kind of useful to know
is just how lovely

00:14:00.294 --> 00:14:01.210
is green space, right?

00:14:01.210 --> 00:14:02.680
Policy makers want
to spend money

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:04.250
on all kinds of
different things.

00:14:04.250 --> 00:14:05.680
They can't spend all their
money on green space.

00:14:05.680 --> 00:14:08.440
And so it's helpful to them to
have some quantitative sense

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:10.140
of the loveliness
of green space,

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:12.610
also blue space, other kinds
of natural environment.

00:14:12.610 --> 00:14:16.840
So how much happier are people
in natural environments?

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:18.580
Economists looking at
this have generally

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:20.050
done big observational studies.

00:14:20.050 --> 00:14:21.800
And they've looked at
countrywide averages

00:14:21.800 --> 00:14:23.050
of happiness and environment.

00:14:23.050 --> 00:14:25.008
Or they've looked at
people's general happiness

00:14:25.008 --> 00:14:27.310
on the individual level in
relation to where they live

00:14:27.310 --> 00:14:29.110
and their immediate
surroundings.

00:14:29.110 --> 00:14:31.026
There are some problems
with those approaches.

00:14:31.026 --> 00:14:33.150
So what I kind of set out
in the PhD thinking was,

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:34.650
wouldn't it be nice
if we could look

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:36.600
at the experiences
of individuals

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:37.850
at particular moments in time?

00:14:37.850 --> 00:14:39.683
So not just how happy
do you feel in general

00:14:39.683 --> 00:14:42.170
and where do you live, but how
happy do you feel right now,

00:14:42.170 --> 00:14:43.540
and where are you right now?

00:14:43.540 --> 00:14:45.490
And that will give you
some really direct data

00:14:45.490 --> 00:14:47.260
on the link between
happiness and environment.

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:49.676
And it would need to be that
hedonic account of happiness,

00:14:49.676 --> 00:14:51.430
that smiley face
feeling, because that's

00:14:51.430 --> 00:14:53.260
the thing that varies sort
of minute by minute and hour

00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:53.680
by hour.

00:14:53.680 --> 00:14:54.970
If you were to ask
people how satisfied

00:14:54.970 --> 00:14:56.500
they were with their
life as a whole

00:14:56.500 --> 00:14:58.990
in different environments,
you wouldn't probably

00:14:58.990 --> 00:15:01.614
get very much if you tried
to do that every day.

00:15:01.614 --> 00:15:03.530
Now, looking at people's
momentary experiences

00:15:03.530 --> 00:15:06.150
has been done for many
years in psychology

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:07.140
and also in medicine.

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:09.556
In psychology, these are called
Experience Sampling Method

00:15:09.556 --> 00:15:10.140
studies.

00:15:10.140 --> 00:15:12.598
In medicine, they're called
Ecological Momentary Assessment

00:15:12.598 --> 00:15:13.110
studies.

00:15:13.110 --> 00:15:14.984
And Alex tells me,
actually, that some of you

00:15:14.984 --> 00:15:19.550
are running something very much
like a Ecological Momentary

00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:23.370
Assessment study at the
moment, using watches.

00:15:23.370 --> 00:15:25.419
But in the classic ESM
survey, certainly when

00:15:25.419 --> 00:15:27.210
these things were come
up with decades ago,

00:15:27.210 --> 00:15:28.980
you would give out
notebooks or PDAs.

00:15:28.980 --> 00:15:30.480
You beeped people
at random moments,

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:32.550
and you asked people
about their experience

00:15:32.550 --> 00:15:34.400
and the context of
their experience.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:37.122
And the benefit of this,
you get no recall bias.

00:15:37.122 --> 00:15:39.330
You get an accurate and
detailed record of experience

00:15:39.330 --> 00:15:41.129
that isn't affected
by the things

00:15:41.129 --> 00:15:42.795
that, for example,
Kahneman talks about,

00:15:42.795 --> 00:15:45.454
about the peak/end rule and
all of the kinds of biases.

00:15:45.454 --> 00:15:47.370
There's an interesting
philosophical question,

00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:48.420
actually, about
whether you are more

00:15:48.420 --> 00:15:49.680
interested in what
you experience

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:50.580
or what you remember.

00:15:50.580 --> 00:15:51.750
But certainly you
can make an argument

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:54.160
that it's nice to have no
recall bias in this data.

00:15:54.160 --> 00:15:55.230
And we get panel data.

00:15:55.230 --> 00:15:56.554
We get longitudinal data.

00:15:56.554 --> 00:15:58.470
And that means we can
do fixed effects models,

00:15:58.470 --> 00:16:02.110
where we only use the
variation within an individual.

00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:04.454
And that's a big benefit.

00:16:04.454 --> 00:16:06.120
If you want to think
about that benefit,

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:09.000
here's a green space in London,
Buckingham Palace Gardens.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.650
And if we went and found
that responses from people

00:16:10.650 --> 00:16:12.390
in Buckingham Palace Gardens
were generally happier

00:16:12.390 --> 00:16:14.280
than the average, you
might want to argue

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:16.320
that the kind of people you find
in Buckingham Palace Gardens

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:17.640
are not quite the
same as the average,

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:19.640
and more likely to have
just been bought a yacht

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:20.874
by the taxpayer, for example.

00:16:20.874 --> 00:16:22.290
There are all kinds
of reasons why

00:16:22.290 --> 00:16:24.795
those people might be happier.

00:16:24.795 --> 00:16:26.170
But with the fixed
effects model,

00:16:26.170 --> 00:16:28.336
when we're looking only
within individual variation,

00:16:28.336 --> 00:16:31.410
we can tell that the same people
in Buckingham Palace Gardens

00:16:31.410 --> 00:16:33.271
are happier than
when those people are

00:16:33.271 --> 00:16:34.770
on the other side
of the wall facing

00:16:34.770 --> 00:16:37.669
lots of buses driving past them
on their bicycle, for example.

00:16:37.669 --> 00:16:39.210
And so this is a
kind of powerful way

00:16:39.210 --> 00:16:40.626
of looking at this,
because we get

00:16:40.626 --> 00:16:42.400
to use that within
individual variation

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.570
and take out effects that say
that certain people are found

00:16:45.570 --> 00:16:47.900
in nice environments and
those are different people

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:51.120
than go elsewhere.

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:53.730
And then around this time with
the PhD, the iPhone launched.

00:16:53.730 --> 00:16:55.950
And then apps became
available for the iPhone.

00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:57.408
And this seemed a
great tool to us.

00:16:57.408 --> 00:16:59.185
So ESM studies
began in the '70s,

00:16:59.185 --> 00:17:00.810
and they were kind
of difficult to run,

00:17:00.810 --> 00:17:03.300
because you had to
give out these diaries.

00:17:03.300 --> 00:17:04.680
You had to give
out these pagers.

00:17:04.680 --> 00:17:06.089
And they found that
in some studies,

00:17:06.089 --> 00:17:08.089
almost half the people
filled in all the diaries

00:17:08.089 --> 00:17:10.990
at the beginning to get it out
of the way with, or at the end,

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:13.170
because they realized
they haven't done it yet.

00:17:13.170 --> 00:17:15.420
And it's a real
logistical challenge,

00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:19.200
whereas with the iPhone and
now with other similar devices

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:21.720
which I'm told exist,
you've got GPS.

00:17:21.720 --> 00:17:23.460
You've got a microphone
for sound levels.

00:17:23.460 --> 00:17:26.744
You can send the data back
using a mobile data connection.

00:17:26.744 --> 00:17:28.910
You can interrupt people
with a noise at any moment.

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:31.350
You can even have them take
a picture of the environment.

00:17:31.350 --> 00:17:35.250
And of course almost everyone
now has one of these things.

00:17:35.250 --> 00:17:38.490
And there was a problem, which
is that certain kinds of people

00:17:38.490 --> 00:17:39.090
have iPhones.

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:42.150
And I suppose certain kinds of
people have Android phones too.

00:17:42.150 --> 00:17:44.700
Certainly in 2010, iPhone
owners are on average

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:46.897
sort of young and
rich and educated.

00:17:46.897 --> 00:17:48.730
And they have to
self-select into the study.

00:17:48.730 --> 00:17:50.430
And then they have to be
able and willing to respond

00:17:50.430 --> 00:17:50.929
to a beep.

00:17:50.929 --> 00:17:53.520
So certainly, we don't
have anything approaching

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:54.970
a representative sample.

00:17:54.970 --> 00:17:57.450
And you can grill me on
that later if you want to.

00:17:57.450 --> 00:18:00.484
But if I do want to take
part, then 2010, 2011, 2012,

00:18:00.484 --> 00:18:02.400
which is when most of
our respondents are for,

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:04.390
it's a free download
in the app store.

00:18:04.390 --> 00:18:06.690
I spend two or three
minutes signing up.

00:18:06.690 --> 00:18:08.760
And then I get dinged.

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:12.810
And then I spend sort of
30 seconds or so responding

00:18:12.810 --> 00:18:15.836
to a series of questions.

00:18:15.836 --> 00:18:16.710
I say how happy I am.

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:18.335
And that's mostly
the data that we use.

00:18:18.335 --> 00:18:21.120
That's mostly the dependent
variable in the regressions

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:22.770
that I'll tell you
about in a minute.

00:18:22.770 --> 00:18:24.480
And then I report a
few control variables

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:25.830
which sometimes
turn out to be quite

00:18:25.830 --> 00:18:26.760
interesting in their own right.

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:28.384
But I say who I'm
with, what I'm doing.

00:18:28.384 --> 00:18:32.130
I think at this point that I'm
imagining that I'm in a pub.

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:35.170
And this will relate to one of
the things I talk about later.

00:18:35.170 --> 00:18:37.330
And then all the
data gets sent back.

00:18:37.330 --> 00:18:39.270
I can look at my
data in the app,

00:18:39.270 --> 00:18:40.844
get some very
simple information.

00:18:40.844 --> 00:18:42.260
I think actually
just being caused

00:18:42.260 --> 00:18:44.250
to reflect on your
happiness twice a day

00:18:44.250 --> 00:18:47.650
is more powerful, probably,
than a few simple charts.

00:18:47.650 --> 00:18:49.200
There's also a sort
of adjacent API

00:18:49.200 --> 00:18:51.960
where I can build
things off this.

00:18:51.960 --> 00:18:53.820
And there's even a kind
of an online section

00:18:53.820 --> 00:18:57.600
where I can look at my
data on the Google map.

00:18:57.600 --> 00:18:58.350
I can view charts.

00:18:58.350 --> 00:19:00.750
I can look at all my
pictures, and so on.

00:19:00.750 --> 00:19:03.619
And there's me working on
Mappiness website, I think.

00:19:03.619 --> 00:19:05.410
The project got really
good media coverage.

00:19:05.410 --> 00:19:06.870
I was sort of thinking,
this is a PhD.

00:19:06.870 --> 00:19:08.786
I might get 100 people
doing it for two weeks.

00:19:08.786 --> 00:19:10.410
That would be fine
for a PhD thesis.

00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:11.650
But actually, we
launched in August,

00:19:11.650 --> 00:19:14.066
which was a great idea, because
nothing happens in August.

00:19:14.066 --> 00:19:16.940
And so we got really nice
coverage, interview on CNN,

00:19:16.940 --> 00:19:18.930
front page of "Le Figaro,"
not quite so useful

00:19:18.930 --> 00:19:20.130
because we're not
targeting France.

00:19:20.130 --> 00:19:22.010
But anyway, Tuesday
is worse than Monday,

00:19:22.010 --> 00:19:24.090
and that's a really big story.

00:19:24.090 --> 00:19:27.060
Featured in the app
store, so that now we

00:19:27.060 --> 00:19:28.770
have more than 4
million responses

00:19:28.770 --> 00:19:30.809
from about 66,000 people.

00:19:30.809 --> 00:19:33.100
And if I give you some sort
of very simple descriptive,

00:19:33.100 --> 00:19:35.880
this is the first year of
data and a half hour moving

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:38.124
average of how happy
people report being.

00:19:38.124 --> 00:19:39.790
It's a little bit
washed out at the top,

00:19:39.790 --> 00:19:43.620
but the left I think
starts at 8:00 AM,

00:19:43.620 --> 00:19:45.290
and the right ends at 10:00 AM.

00:19:45.290 --> 00:19:47.040
And then there's a
sort of horizontal line

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:50.640
per day through the year from
the beginning of September 2010

00:19:50.640 --> 00:19:52.640
to the end of August 2011.

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:55.260
And a few patterns
might jump out at you.

00:19:55.260 --> 00:19:56.752
Firstly, it's stripey.

00:19:56.752 --> 00:19:57.960
And the stripes are weekends.

00:19:57.960 --> 00:20:00.780
So you can see lighter
colors are happier.

00:20:00.780 --> 00:20:04.309
Weekends are enormously
happier than weekdays.

00:20:04.309 --> 00:20:06.350
There's a kind of really
bright spot around here,

00:20:06.350 --> 00:20:07.550
which is Christmas.

00:20:07.550 --> 00:20:09.383
And there's a really
bright spot around here

00:20:09.383 --> 00:20:11.257
which is sort of the
May bank holidays.

00:20:11.257 --> 00:20:13.340
We get a little bit lighter
as we go from the left

00:20:13.340 --> 00:20:15.860
to the right, which tells
you that, on average, people

00:20:15.860 --> 00:20:17.565
get happier throughout the day.

00:20:17.565 --> 00:20:19.940
And you can also see that the
second half is a little bit

00:20:19.940 --> 00:20:21.170
noisier than the
first half, so you

00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:23.711
can tell that we had slightly
more respondents in this period

00:20:23.711 --> 00:20:26.330
than we did in this period.

00:20:26.330 --> 00:20:29.370
This actually now
goes over the whole 6

00:20:29.370 --> 00:20:31.950
and 1/2 years up to the
beginning of this year.

00:20:31.950 --> 00:20:33.620
It's probably too
small to see, which

00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:35.578
is sort of vaguely
intentional, because I still

00:20:35.578 --> 00:20:36.620
haven't published this.

00:20:36.620 --> 00:20:38.780
But you can see these
peaks are all Christmases.

00:20:38.780 --> 00:20:40.260
Christmases are always good.

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:42.320
There's a general
downward tendency.

00:20:42.320 --> 00:20:43.940
I don't know whether we should
make anything of that or not.

00:20:43.940 --> 00:20:45.898
It might just be that
different kinds of people

00:20:45.898 --> 00:20:48.140
were signed up later than
were signed up earlier.

00:20:48.140 --> 00:20:50.129
So maybe some face
validity for saying

00:20:50.129 --> 00:20:51.920
that people are a little
bit less happy now

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:52.878
than they were in 2010?

00:20:52.878 --> 00:20:55.295
But I couldn't guarantee
you that from the data.

00:20:55.295 --> 00:20:57.470
A few other events
that we can spot.

00:20:57.470 --> 00:21:00.340
Murray winning Wimbledon
here on a hot day.

00:21:00.340 --> 00:21:03.864
Hot days of above
about 25 degrees,

00:21:03.864 --> 00:21:05.530
you get a really big
spike in happiness.

00:21:05.530 --> 00:21:07.130
Other weather variables
make a difference, but not

00:21:07.130 --> 00:21:08.046
such a big difference.

00:21:08.046 --> 00:21:09.830
But really hot
weather is very good.

00:21:09.830 --> 00:21:14.060
Olympic opening
ceremony, royal wedding,

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:16.380
annoying for Republicans.

00:21:16.380 --> 00:21:17.900
And you probably
can't read this,

00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:19.525
but it relates to
one of the questions.

00:21:19.525 --> 00:21:22.280
This is the worst,
the least happy day

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:25.270
that we recorded over the
whole of the 6 and 1/2 years.

00:21:25.270 --> 00:21:27.490
And this is the news
that Trump got elected

00:21:27.490 --> 00:21:29.450
as the president of America.

00:21:29.450 --> 00:21:32.900
This is, I think,
the Brexit result.

00:21:32.900 --> 00:21:35.727
I think that's the
fourth least happy day.

00:21:35.727 --> 00:21:37.310
Now, you might say
this just shows you

00:21:37.310 --> 00:21:39.101
that Mappiness users
are not representative

00:21:39.101 --> 00:21:39.970
of the population.

00:21:39.970 --> 00:21:41.470
On the other hand,
referendum voters

00:21:41.470 --> 00:21:44.010
are not representative
of the population either.

00:21:44.010 --> 00:21:47.000
And Mappiness voters
have great taste.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.870
So I seem to have made
a more political point

00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:52.526
than I intended.

00:21:52.526 --> 00:21:54.650
Planning to use this to
create a happiness forecast

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:55.100
at some point.

00:21:55.100 --> 00:21:56.933
And I've been planning
this for a long time.

00:21:56.933 --> 00:21:59.630
But there's this idea of
Blue Monday every year.

00:21:59.630 --> 00:22:01.080
It's the second
Monday in January.

00:22:01.080 --> 00:22:03.680
They kind of wheel out the guy
who came up with Blue Monday.

00:22:03.680 --> 00:22:05.010
And sometimes they
wheel me out to say

00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:06.176
that Blue Monday is rubbish.

00:22:06.176 --> 00:22:08.832
But we've got no evidence that
the second Monday in January

00:22:08.832 --> 00:22:10.040
is anything particularly bad.

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:12.234
If anything, it looks
like a Tuesday in November

00:22:12.234 --> 00:22:14.150
might be the worst day
of the year on average.

00:22:14.150 --> 00:22:17.300
But I hope to have news on
that in the near future.

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:19.790
Now, in Mappiness I was
interested in green spaces.

00:22:19.790 --> 00:22:22.090
And so as an incredibly
naive first approach,

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:24.530
this is measuring the
number of green pixels

00:22:24.530 --> 00:22:26.250
in each of the pictures
that people take.

00:22:26.250 --> 00:22:28.304
These are the colors that
I'm counting as green.

00:22:28.304 --> 00:22:30.470
And this is some indication
of how many pixels there

00:22:30.470 --> 00:22:31.830
are in each one.

00:22:31.830 --> 00:22:34.514
It was done very
simply in processing.

00:22:34.514 --> 00:22:35.930
Interestingly, the
amount of green

00:22:35.930 --> 00:22:38.210
is very strongly
correlated with happiness

00:22:38.210 --> 00:22:39.860
before we control
for anything else.

00:22:39.860 --> 00:22:42.290
So no green pixels
to all green pixels

00:22:42.290 --> 00:22:46.416
gives you about six points
out of 100 jump in happiness.

00:22:46.416 --> 00:22:48.290
I'm not sure we can read
very much into that,

00:22:48.290 --> 00:22:49.700
because the effect
goes away when

00:22:49.700 --> 00:22:50.650
we control for other things.

00:22:50.650 --> 00:22:52.370
It might well be, for
example, that people really

00:22:52.370 --> 00:22:54.494
don't like work and that
workplaces generally don't

00:22:54.494 --> 00:22:56.120
have a lot of green in them.

00:22:56.120 --> 00:22:58.369
And it could be
as simple as that.

00:22:58.369 --> 00:23:00.160
I've also been thinking
about deep learning

00:23:00.160 --> 00:23:01.201
for image classification.

00:23:01.201 --> 00:23:03.326
There's about 300,000
photos, so that could be fun.

00:23:03.326 --> 00:23:05.534
I'm sure there's lots of
other kinds of deep learning

00:23:05.534 --> 00:23:07.190
that can be done with this data.

00:23:07.190 --> 00:23:10.550
But for the PhD, and the more
serious analysis in the PhD,

00:23:10.550 --> 00:23:13.404
I joined up habitat data
with each response location.

00:23:13.404 --> 00:23:15.320
And this is an extract
from the Land Cover Map

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:19.190
2000, which is a high resolution
remote sense satellite

00:23:19.190 --> 00:23:19.854
data set.

00:23:19.854 --> 00:23:21.770
This is London, so you
can see a lot of black,

00:23:21.770 --> 00:23:22.955
which is continuous urban.

00:23:22.955 --> 00:23:24.680
But you can also see the river.

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:27.240
You can also see Hyde
Park as a mixture of trees

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:28.380
and grassland and so on.

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:30.470
So this is not about
country versus city.

00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:33.284
It's very much about land
cover wherever it occurs.

00:23:33.284 --> 00:23:35.200
And then all the information
that we collected

00:23:35.200 --> 00:23:37.200
goes into one big
regression model.

00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:39.920
So it predicts happiness from
naught to 100 on the left,

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:42.051
with on the right the
habitat that you're in,

00:23:42.051 --> 00:23:44.300
the weather conditions, the
daylight, who you're with,

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.010
what you're doing, what kind of
place you're in, time of day,

00:23:47.010 --> 00:23:49.343
day of the week, how many
responses you've given before,

00:23:49.343 --> 00:23:51.500
because we find that people
get happier over time,

00:23:51.500 --> 00:23:53.458
and we use individual
fixed effects to take out

00:23:53.458 --> 00:23:55.602
that average effect
of being each person.

00:23:55.602 --> 00:23:56.810
And these all go in together.

00:23:56.810 --> 00:23:58.685
And that means that each
effect is controlled

00:23:58.685 --> 00:23:59.690
for every other effect.

00:23:59.690 --> 00:24:02.169
That's important, because when
you're out in a green space,

00:24:02.169 --> 00:24:03.710
it might also be
sunny, and you might

00:24:03.710 --> 00:24:05.168
be playing Frisbee
with your mates,

00:24:05.168 --> 00:24:07.240
and it might be the
weekend, and so on.

00:24:07.240 --> 00:24:10.640
So this all goes together to
this big regression model.

00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:12.450
To get a feel for the
size of the effects,

00:24:12.450 --> 00:24:14.950
you can look at the happiest
and the least happy activities.

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:16.730
The top activity
is one that I added

00:24:16.730 --> 00:24:18.937
after many emailed requests.

00:24:18.937 --> 00:24:21.020
There may be people looking
over people's shoulder

00:24:21.020 --> 00:24:23.570
at this point, so we take
that one with a pinch of salt.

00:24:23.570 --> 00:24:25.028
But you can see
that generally it's

00:24:25.028 --> 00:24:27.740
sort of physical activities
and cultural activities

00:24:27.740 --> 00:24:31.150
and social activities that
seem to occupy the top spots.

00:24:31.150 --> 00:24:33.365
And most of these
give a give a bump

00:24:33.365 --> 00:24:35.660
of sort of four to
six points out of 100

00:24:35.660 --> 00:24:36.890
in people's happiness.

00:24:36.890 --> 00:24:39.570
We've got plenty of data, and
so these are the 95% confidence

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:40.070
intervals.

00:24:40.070 --> 00:24:42.980
So these are very
significant effects.

00:24:42.980 --> 00:24:46.760
And then the focus of the
research, which was land cover.

00:24:46.760 --> 00:24:49.040
And we find this
land cover type,

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:50.780
marine and coastal margins.

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:53.360
People were enormously happier
in marine and coastal margins

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:54.436
than anywhere else.

00:24:54.436 --> 00:24:55.310
This is all relative.

00:24:55.310 --> 00:24:58.710
Zero here is being in
an urban environment.

00:24:58.710 --> 00:25:02.350
So people are on average about
six points happier in what's

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:03.320
effectively an estuary.

00:25:03.320 --> 00:25:05.130
This is a kind of an
estuary environment,

00:25:05.130 --> 00:25:06.254
marine and coastal margins.

00:25:06.254 --> 00:25:07.749
It's not any coastline.

00:25:07.749 --> 00:25:09.290
But in any other
natural environment,

00:25:09.290 --> 00:25:11.450
they're also
significantly happier

00:25:11.450 --> 00:25:13.370
than they would be in
an urban environment

00:25:13.370 --> 00:25:15.328
after we've controlled
for all the other things

00:25:15.328 --> 00:25:17.019
that we can think of.

00:25:17.019 --> 00:25:19.560
And this stands up to a number
of different robustness checks

00:25:19.560 --> 00:25:21.230
and some completely
different ways of defining

00:25:21.230 --> 00:25:22.146
a natural environment.

00:25:22.146 --> 00:25:24.140
So it works very
similarly if we use

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:28.260
areas of outstanding natural
beauty, national nature

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:31.415
reserves, and one other
the classification

00:25:31.415 --> 00:25:32.270
that I forget now.

00:25:32.270 --> 00:25:34.592
But different kind of
administrative classifications

00:25:34.592 --> 00:25:36.800
of countryside give us sort
of similar sized results.

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:40.520
And people are happier in
those than they are outside.

00:25:40.520 --> 00:25:43.114
And so this was reported in a
paper in the journal "Global

00:25:43.114 --> 00:25:44.030
Environmental Change."

00:25:44.030 --> 00:25:46.437
A strong line of evidence
on links between environment

00:25:46.437 --> 00:25:47.020
and happiness.

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:48.110
Slightly ambitious title.

00:25:48.110 --> 00:25:48.943
This is only the UK.

00:25:48.943 --> 00:25:50.130
It's not representative.

00:25:50.130 --> 00:25:52.490
But anyway, we've got some
nice quantitative evidence

00:25:52.490 --> 00:25:53.960
on this point.

00:25:53.960 --> 00:25:55.952
And that's nice,
because we all probably,

00:25:55.952 --> 00:25:57.410
as I said at the
beginning, realize

00:25:57.410 --> 00:25:58.924
that people like green spaces.

00:25:58.924 --> 00:26:01.340
But this generally sounds a
little bit soft and intangible

00:26:01.340 --> 00:26:02.990
and perhaps doesn't
stop the government

00:26:02.990 --> 00:26:04.545
proposing to
privatize our forests

00:26:04.545 --> 00:26:06.920
or allowing them to bulldoze
sites of scientific interest

00:26:06.920 --> 00:26:08.044
for golf courses and so on.

00:26:08.044 --> 00:26:09.950
And so the more hard
quantitative data

00:26:09.950 --> 00:26:12.440
we've got on this, perhaps
the better the chance

00:26:12.440 --> 00:26:15.440
we might have in saving some
of the environmental treasures

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:17.090
that we've got.

00:26:17.090 --> 00:26:19.310
So we've covered
being by an estuary.

00:26:19.310 --> 00:26:20.239
That's really good.

00:26:20.239 --> 00:26:22.655
And we've covered Donald Trump
winning the election, which

00:26:22.655 --> 00:26:24.180
is very bad.

00:26:24.180 --> 00:26:26.450
We've got a number of
things left in this list

00:26:26.450 --> 00:26:27.932
that I promised you.

00:26:27.932 --> 00:26:29.390
Any of you that
are werewolves will

00:26:29.390 --> 00:26:30.806
be interested to
know that I don't

00:26:30.806 --> 00:26:34.090
find any effect of the full moon
or any other phase of the moon,

00:26:34.090 --> 00:26:36.590
although I do have to control
quite carefully for other time

00:26:36.590 --> 00:26:40.070
variables in order to not get
interesting false positives

00:26:40.070 --> 00:26:40.940
on that point.

00:26:40.940 --> 00:26:44.960
And that leaves us with
drinking, riots, and football.

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:48.080
Unsurprisingly, we do find
that alcohol, drinking alcohol,

00:26:48.080 --> 00:26:53.510
makes people happier in the
moment than when you're not

00:26:53.510 --> 00:26:54.290
drinking alcohol.

00:26:54.290 --> 00:26:56.623
And that's after controlling
for lots of the things that

00:26:56.623 --> 00:26:59.360
go along with drinking alcohol,
such as probably not working,

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:02.192
being with friends, being
in a pub, and so on.

00:27:02.192 --> 00:27:03.650
And we also see it
making you tired

00:27:03.650 --> 00:27:06.830
the next day, which
is not rocket science.

00:27:06.830 --> 00:27:08.840
These were back of the
envelope calculations

00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:10.465
for the cabinet office
who were looking

00:27:10.465 --> 00:27:12.620
for evidence of the
benefits of local pubs

00:27:12.620 --> 00:27:13.987
as sort of community hubs.

00:27:13.987 --> 00:27:16.070
These, again, are fixed
effects regression results

00:27:16.070 --> 00:27:17.970
controlling for a whole
range of other things.

00:27:17.970 --> 00:27:19.280
And we don't know what
people are drinking.

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:21.049
We don't know how
much they're drinking.

00:27:21.049 --> 00:27:23.090
But we do find a big
positive effect of drinking,

00:27:23.090 --> 00:27:25.740
six points out of
100 in happiness.

00:27:25.740 --> 00:27:27.510
And that's very significant.

00:27:27.510 --> 00:27:28.550
And then we have some
other interaction.

00:27:28.550 --> 00:27:30.675
Drinking in the pub is
better, drinking on your own

00:27:30.675 --> 00:27:33.540
is significantly
worse, and so on.

00:27:33.540 --> 00:27:35.330
Now, that's the basis
of another paper.

00:27:35.330 --> 00:27:36.980
And, of course, that's not
the whole of the well-being

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:37.880
story with alcohol, right?

00:27:37.880 --> 00:27:40.280
We saw negative coefficients
on drinking alone, drinking

00:27:40.280 --> 00:27:41.322
on a weekday morning.

00:27:41.322 --> 00:27:43.280
There are, of course,
drinkers and non drinkers

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:45.440
who have their lives
wrecked by alcohol.

00:27:45.440 --> 00:27:47.676
But the positive effects
are part of the story.

00:27:47.676 --> 00:27:49.300
And actually, some
recent research work

00:27:49.300 --> 00:27:51.320
and some recent
policy work often

00:27:51.320 --> 00:27:54.209
can entirely neglect to
mention the positive reasons

00:27:54.209 --> 00:27:55.250
why people drink as well.

00:27:55.250 --> 00:27:57.712
So it is useful to be
able to quantify those.

00:27:57.712 --> 00:27:59.420
And that's the point
that my coauthor Ben

00:27:59.420 --> 00:28:03.230
Bamburg makes in this paper.

00:28:03.230 --> 00:28:05.720
I have very little
interest in football,

00:28:05.720 --> 00:28:10.570
but some of my colleagues at
Sussex are football fanatics.

00:28:10.570 --> 00:28:13.460
And it seems to be a source of
strong emotion for some people,

00:28:13.460 --> 00:28:16.190
judging by these quotes
that I've picked out.

00:28:19.290 --> 00:28:21.780
And so we figured out that
actually with the Mappiness

00:28:21.780 --> 00:28:23.880
data, we can look at this.

00:28:23.880 --> 00:28:26.760
And we have responses like
this one, which occurs here,

00:28:26.760 --> 00:28:30.450
kind of very close to
the football stands,

00:28:30.450 --> 00:28:32.160
middle of the afternoon
on a Saturday.

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:34.910
And the individual reports that
they're at a match or sporting

00:28:34.910 --> 00:28:35.730
event.

00:28:35.730 --> 00:28:38.860
So we found a data set with the
locations of football stadiums.

00:28:38.860 --> 00:28:41.380
We found another data set
that has match dates, results,

00:28:41.380 --> 00:28:42.625
and the bookmakers' odds.

00:28:42.625 --> 00:28:44.250
And we did a little
bit of web scraping

00:28:44.250 --> 00:28:47.040
to find the exact kickoff
times of those matches.

00:28:47.040 --> 00:28:49.370
And then we could join all
that together to figure out

00:28:49.370 --> 00:28:52.200
who seem to be keen football
supporters, which teams they

00:28:52.200 --> 00:28:52.830
follow.

00:28:52.830 --> 00:28:54.450
Ideally you spot them
at two different matches

00:28:54.450 --> 00:28:56.930
with one team in common and
then you're reasonably certain.

00:28:56.930 --> 00:28:59.774
And we get 100 or
200 people that way.

00:28:59.774 --> 00:29:01.440
And we get a few
hundred more if we just

00:29:01.440 --> 00:29:04.362
assume that people are probably
supporting the home team.

00:29:04.362 --> 00:29:06.570
And then we can follow those
people's happiness level

00:29:06.570 --> 00:29:07.519
throughout the season.

00:29:07.519 --> 00:29:09.060
We're not limited
just to the matches

00:29:09.060 --> 00:29:10.140
that we spot on the map.

00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:12.760
And this is actually a paper
that I'm working on right now.

00:29:12.760 --> 00:29:14.970
And what we find is
interesting and very much

00:29:14.970 --> 00:29:17.340
in line with sort of the
behavioral economics on loss

00:29:17.340 --> 00:29:18.100
aversion.

00:29:18.100 --> 00:29:21.810
So we find that a win is sort
of niceish for an hour or two.

00:29:21.810 --> 00:29:23.610
A loss is really bad.

00:29:23.610 --> 00:29:26.610
It's much more negative
than a win is positive.

00:29:26.610 --> 00:29:29.290
And not only is it much worse,
it also lasts much longer.

00:29:29.290 --> 00:29:31.230
So you can still
see the next morning

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:33.510
that people are unhappy
if their team lost,

00:29:33.510 --> 00:29:35.579
even more so if they
didn't see it coming.

00:29:35.579 --> 00:29:37.370
So if you also have an
interaction in there

00:29:37.370 --> 00:29:39.703
for the bookies' odds being
that they were going to win,

00:29:39.703 --> 00:29:43.460
and then they lost, that
makes it even more painful.

00:29:43.460 --> 00:29:46.350
And actually, this does have
some quite interesting sort

00:29:46.350 --> 00:29:48.000
of real world outcomes as well.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:49.840
There was a paper in
the "Quarterly Journal

00:29:49.840 --> 00:29:51.394
of Economics" about
American football

00:29:51.394 --> 00:29:53.310
and looking at domestic
violence that came out

00:29:53.310 --> 00:29:55.772
with very strong findings.

00:29:55.772 --> 00:29:57.980
And we may also be able to
look at people's behavior.

00:29:57.980 --> 00:30:00.000
We haven't done this yet,
but kind of quite interested

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.541
to find out whether
it has any effect

00:30:01.541 --> 00:30:04.500
on the probability of showing
up at work the next day.

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:06.960
So that leaves us with
riots, I think, of the things

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:09.120
that I promised to
talk to you about.

00:30:09.120 --> 00:30:11.504
And this is work that was
done by my PhD student

00:30:11.504 --> 00:30:13.420
[? Panka ?] [INAUDIBLE]
who wanted to be here,

00:30:13.420 --> 00:30:15.810
but unfortunately isn't
quite back from the States

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:17.040
on a Fulbright scholarship.

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:18.540
This follows on
from some work where

00:30:18.540 --> 00:30:19.998
we looked at
happiness impacts sort

00:30:19.998 --> 00:30:22.560
of rippling over time and
space from terrorist incidents

00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:23.707
in Northern Ireland.

00:30:23.707 --> 00:30:25.290
So [? Panka ?] took
the Mappiness data

00:30:25.290 --> 00:30:26.914
and was looking for
a sort of signature

00:30:26.914 --> 00:30:30.034
from the riots that happened in
August 2011 in English cities.

00:30:30.034 --> 00:30:31.950
And if you weren't here
or you don't remember,

00:30:31.950 --> 00:30:33.960
there were sort of
several days of looting

00:30:33.960 --> 00:30:36.460
and setting fire to things and
clashing with the police that

00:30:36.460 --> 00:30:38.190
started, I think, in
Hackney, and spread

00:30:38.190 --> 00:30:40.887
to other parts of London and
then the country as a whole.

00:30:40.887 --> 00:30:42.720
Now, that seemed
reasonably promising to me,

00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:44.820
because I was living close
to Elephant and Castle

00:30:44.820 --> 00:30:47.430
at the time, and I remember
that we were planning to go out

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:49.772
to a restaurant and then we
thought maybe the Elephant

00:30:49.772 --> 00:30:51.480
and Castle shopping
center isn't the best

00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:53.100
place to be at this point.

00:30:53.100 --> 00:30:55.470
So I thought you'd have seen
it in my happiness data.

00:30:55.470 --> 00:30:56.640
[? Panka ?] hasn't
actually managed

00:30:56.640 --> 00:30:58.931
to find this in the Mappiness
data, which I don't think

00:30:58.931 --> 00:31:02.000
is her fault. I think
we just don't see it.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:03.600
All that we do
see is that we can

00:31:03.600 --> 00:31:05.190
see that people are watching
telly a little bit more

00:31:05.190 --> 00:31:06.780
over this period,
which is potentially

00:31:06.780 --> 00:31:09.870
people keeping track with
what's going on on the news.

00:31:09.870 --> 00:31:10.930
We're not quite sure.

00:31:10.930 --> 00:31:12.660
But as far as we can
tell, these riots

00:31:12.660 --> 00:31:16.666
don't have an impact on
your average Mappiness user.

00:31:16.666 --> 00:31:18.540
So that's all the things
that I promised you,

00:31:18.540 --> 00:31:20.080
but how are you doing today?

00:31:20.080 --> 00:31:21.880
Well, the bad news, obviously,
is that you're at work.

00:31:21.880 --> 00:31:23.796
And of all the things
that you could be doing,

00:31:23.796 --> 00:31:26.774
work ranks second only to
sickness as a cause of misery.

00:31:26.774 --> 00:31:28.440
These are all the
activities that people

00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:29.690
can report doing in Mappiness.

00:31:29.690 --> 00:31:31.460
There's about 40 of them.

00:31:31.460 --> 00:31:33.262
And here is working or studying.

00:31:33.262 --> 00:31:35.220
And we can restrict this
just to the people who

00:31:35.220 --> 00:31:36.940
say that they're
in full time work,

00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:39.540
and we find that has quite a
big negative coefficient, second

00:31:39.540 --> 00:31:41.850
only to being ill in bed,
which is rather bigger.

00:31:41.850 --> 00:31:45.917
That's 20 points out of 100,
but work is still minus 5.

00:31:45.917 --> 00:31:48.000
And in fact, it's not just
being in the workplace.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:52.810
The working day and working
are independently negative.

00:31:52.810 --> 00:31:54.632
I can't remember how
colleagues turn out.

00:31:54.632 --> 00:31:55.840
Maybe I shouldn't say anyway.

00:31:55.840 --> 00:31:58.220
This is work with
Alex Bryson at UCL.

00:31:58.220 --> 00:32:01.980
And we also look at what you're
doing while you're working.

00:32:01.980 --> 00:32:05.850
And we find, in fact,
that only 0.3% of people

00:32:05.850 --> 00:32:07.440
follow Snow White's
advice, which

00:32:07.440 --> 00:32:10.250
is a pity, because the
happiness effects of singing

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:13.500
and performing would be just
about enough to wipe out

00:32:13.500 --> 00:32:16.350
the negative effects of
working, although the effects

00:32:16.350 --> 00:32:19.000
on your coworkers might also
need to be factored in there,

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:20.432
I suppose.

00:32:20.432 --> 00:32:22.890
So there were two other things
that I want to mention today

00:32:22.890 --> 00:32:24.270
in terms of what
we've been doing

00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:25.690
and what we're going to do next.

00:32:25.690 --> 00:32:27.690
And I mention these two
things particularly just

00:32:27.690 --> 00:32:29.909
in case anyone here
is sort of interested

00:32:29.909 --> 00:32:31.200
and potentially could help out.

00:32:31.200 --> 00:32:32.710
Now, this is a bit washed out.

00:32:32.710 --> 00:32:34.560
And so my PhD
student, [? Panka ?]

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:36.840
is now sort of turning her
attention to air pollution.

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:38.548
And we've got really
good reason to think

00:32:38.548 --> 00:32:41.250
that air pollution will affect
people's subjective well-being,

00:32:41.250 --> 00:32:43.306
including routes via
their physical health.

00:32:43.306 --> 00:32:44.680
We've also got
really good reason

00:32:44.680 --> 00:32:47.370
to think that it will impair
their physical and cognitive

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:48.060
abilities.

00:32:48.060 --> 00:32:51.000
There's a really amazing
paper last year from LSE

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:53.610
by Sefi Soth, where he gives
quite convincing evidence,

00:32:53.610 --> 00:32:55.890
having kind of put air
pollution monitors in the exam

00:32:55.890 --> 00:32:59.130
rooms at LSE, that high levels
of particulates in the exam

00:32:59.130 --> 00:33:01.170
room increase students'
probability of failing

00:33:01.170 --> 00:33:03.420
their exam by about 5%.

00:33:03.420 --> 00:33:05.640
And he has the same students
sitting different exams

00:33:05.640 --> 00:33:07.764
in different rooms at
different levels of pollution

00:33:07.764 --> 00:33:11.010
so that the identification is
quite convincing in that one.

00:33:11.010 --> 00:33:14.640
Now, I raise this possibility
of a link between air pollution

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:17.420
and performance because
one thing that occurs to us

00:33:17.420 --> 00:33:20.220
is that Google has really rich
data on some kinds of cognitive

00:33:20.220 --> 00:33:22.920
and perhaps also physical
performance, for example, maybe

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:26.520
mistyped searches, mistyped
words on Android keyboard,

00:33:26.520 --> 00:33:27.540
and so on.

00:33:27.540 --> 00:33:30.570
And these data presumably could
be located in space and time.

00:33:30.570 --> 00:33:32.070
And that means that
potentially they

00:33:32.070 --> 00:33:33.960
could be related
to air pollution

00:33:33.960 --> 00:33:36.760
data to look for potentially
causal relationships.

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:38.310
And in cities like
London and lots

00:33:38.310 --> 00:33:40.560
of American cities, different
places around the world,

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:43.400
there's quite good data now
on air pollution through space

00:33:43.400 --> 00:33:44.950
and over time.

00:33:44.950 --> 00:33:46.500
So if you can think
of any data that

00:33:46.500 --> 00:33:48.083
would help us
understand air pollution

00:33:48.083 --> 00:33:50.760
effects on performance, then do
let me know at the end of today

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:52.219
or on email or via Alex.

00:33:52.219 --> 00:33:54.510
It doesn't necessarily have
to be big things, you know,

00:33:54.510 --> 00:33:58.080
thinking about a simple typo.

00:33:58.080 --> 00:34:00.960
A simple typo has been enough in
various situations in the past

00:34:00.960 --> 00:34:03.200
to administer a near
fatal drug dose.

00:34:03.200 --> 00:34:06.489
To lop several nines off
the availability of S-3,

00:34:06.489 --> 00:34:08.280
we'll have the world
believing that there's

00:34:08.280 --> 00:34:10.571
an order of magnitude more
iron in spinach than in fact

00:34:10.571 --> 00:34:13.274
is in spinach, which is the
origin of the Popeye cartoons.

00:34:13.274 --> 00:34:15.690
So even small things, I think,
could be really interesting

00:34:15.690 --> 00:34:16.569
there.

00:34:16.569 --> 00:34:19.110
And the other thing I was going
to talk about, which as I say

00:34:19.110 --> 00:34:22.080
is sort of apposite on the day
after Mappiness kind of goes

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:23.424
dark, is Mappiness 2.

00:34:23.424 --> 00:34:25.590
And there are sort of three
things that distinguish,

00:34:25.590 --> 00:34:28.089
we hope, this next iteration
of Mappiness, which I'm already

00:34:28.089 --> 00:34:29.969
working on, from the original.

00:34:29.969 --> 00:34:32.144
Firstly, it will be
on iPhone and Android,

00:34:32.144 --> 00:34:34.620
and we hope it will add in
some fun stuff like heart rate

00:34:34.620 --> 00:34:36.245
variability measurement
with the camera

00:34:36.245 --> 00:34:39.290
and flash which, I discover,
Alex and some of his team

00:34:39.290 --> 00:34:40.618
know an awful lot about.

00:34:40.618 --> 00:34:42.659
Integration, probably,
with HealthKit and perhaps

00:34:42.659 --> 00:34:46.350
equivalents on Android, which
I'd be happy to talk about.

00:34:46.350 --> 00:34:48.972
It will try to not only
quantify your happiness--

00:34:48.972 --> 00:34:51.305
and as I said, we do find
that the process of reflecting

00:34:51.305 --> 00:34:52.980
through doing
Mappiness for a while

00:34:52.980 --> 00:34:55.739
does seem to make
people happier--

00:34:55.739 --> 00:34:57.390
but also to improve
your happiness.

00:34:57.390 --> 00:34:58.740
Now the idea in the
original Mappiness

00:34:58.740 --> 00:35:00.720
was just that we wanted data,
so we kind of didn't want

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:02.080
to change people's happiness.

00:35:02.080 --> 00:35:03.840
Obviously it's a good thing
that people's happiness went up

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:05.340
rather than down,
or we'd have a lot

00:35:05.340 --> 00:35:08.120
of trouble getting ethical
approval for any future study.

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:10.530
But it's a little bit cold in
that you can tell Mappiness

00:35:10.530 --> 00:35:12.738
that you're really miserable
day after day after day,

00:35:12.738 --> 00:35:15.360
and Mappiness the original
does nothing about it.

00:35:15.360 --> 00:35:18.000
My co-founder at Psychological
Technologies, Nick Begley,

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:19.530
was the first
employee at Headspace,

00:35:19.530 --> 00:35:21.510
and so he knows plenty
about mindfulness

00:35:21.510 --> 00:35:23.302
and other sorts of
scientifically validated

00:35:23.302 --> 00:35:24.968
approaches to making
people feel better.

00:35:24.968 --> 00:35:27.330
So the idea is that in the
next Mappiness, if you're not

00:35:27.330 --> 00:35:29.280
feeling good, we can
begin to offer you

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:31.530
suggestions for the
kinds of things that

00:35:31.530 --> 00:35:32.790
might make you feel better.

00:35:32.790 --> 00:35:35.580
And for example, we have
mental and physical well-being

00:35:35.580 --> 00:35:38.760
interventions that are
integrated in Mappiness 2,

00:35:38.760 --> 00:35:40.885
like this sort of interactive
mindfulness practice.

00:35:40.885 --> 00:35:42.843
And we can suggest them
at appropriate moments.

00:35:42.843 --> 00:35:44.400
And even better,
hopefully over time,

00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:47.227
we can collect data on what the
most appropriate moments are

00:35:47.227 --> 00:35:49.560
for which kinds of interventions
and how those are going

00:35:49.560 --> 00:35:52.290
to make people feel better.

00:35:52.290 --> 00:35:54.590
And the third thing
that's new in Mappiness

00:35:54.590 --> 00:35:55.770
is more of a focus on work.

00:35:55.770 --> 00:35:57.216
So as I said, the
first Mappiness

00:35:57.216 --> 00:35:58.840
found that people
aren't happy at work.

00:35:58.840 --> 00:36:01.060
And that wasn't what
we set out to do.

00:36:01.060 --> 00:36:03.060
And we therefore didn't
collect lots of the data

00:36:03.060 --> 00:36:04.990
that you'd probably
most want to try and dig

00:36:04.990 --> 00:36:06.319
in to that in more detail.

00:36:06.319 --> 00:36:08.110
You know, we don't know
what sector or even

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:11.220
what company people are working
in, what they do at work,

00:36:11.220 --> 00:36:13.560
anything about what they
think about their employer,

00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:14.405
and so on.

00:36:14.405 --> 00:36:15.780
And this is
obviously information

00:36:15.780 --> 00:36:17.910
that employers are interested
in and that employers

00:36:17.910 --> 00:36:20.190
could use to make the
workplace better and make

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:22.860
people happier at work, as well
as perhaps more productive.

00:36:22.860 --> 00:36:25.350
So we already have employees
in one big household name

00:36:25.350 --> 00:36:28.700
firm using what's effectively
a kind of an alpha version

00:36:28.700 --> 00:36:29.670
of Mappiness 2.

00:36:29.670 --> 00:36:32.406
But we're also looking for
people, and indeed workplaces,

00:36:32.406 --> 00:36:33.780
who would like to
help us conduct

00:36:33.780 --> 00:36:36.732
some kind of randomized
controlled trial on the impacts

00:36:36.732 --> 00:36:38.940
of this sort of technology,
measuring and then trying

00:36:38.940 --> 00:36:43.140
to improve people's
well-being through the apps

00:36:43.140 --> 00:36:45.090
in their pockets.

00:36:45.090 --> 00:36:46.566
So that's it, but
hopefully there's

00:36:46.566 --> 00:36:47.940
plenty of time
for any questions,

00:36:47.940 --> 00:36:49.106
if you've got any questions.

00:36:49.106 --> 00:36:50.390
And thank you for listening.

00:36:50.390 --> 00:36:53.270
