00:38:52.650 --> 00:38:53.566
terrible Christmas is.

00:38:55.981 --> 00:38:58.230
GEORGE MACKERRON: So, I
suppose a lot of it turns out,

00:38:58.230 --> 00:39:00.180
I think, to come back
to how likely people are

00:39:00.180 --> 00:39:01.060
to be working.

00:39:01.060 --> 00:39:02.875
And I suspect that
happiness at Christmas

00:39:02.875 --> 00:39:04.500
is partly driven by
the fact that we've

00:39:04.500 --> 00:39:07.434
got the least number of people
working throughout the year.

00:39:07.434 --> 00:39:09.600
We see bank holidays as
being very positive as well.

00:39:11.979 --> 00:39:13.770
Beyond that, it's just
anecdotes, isn't it?

00:39:13.770 --> 00:39:16.874
I mean, it would be good
to do qualitative research

00:39:16.874 --> 00:39:17.790
in some of this stuff.

00:39:17.790 --> 00:39:20.100
And I guess that's not my area.

00:39:20.100 --> 00:39:24.014
There's perhaps a slight worry
about whether people don't

00:39:24.014 --> 00:39:25.680
report if they're not
happy at Christmas

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:26.940
because they feel
like they should be,

00:39:26.940 --> 00:39:29.130
or if they misrepresent
their happiness at Christmas,

00:39:29.130 --> 00:39:30.680
again because they feel that
that's the time that they're

00:39:30.680 --> 00:39:31.555
supposed to be happy.

00:39:31.555 --> 00:39:33.816
They don't want to
admit that they're not.

00:39:33.816 --> 00:39:35.190
I mean, if you
were going to find

00:39:35.190 --> 00:39:36.870
that in any kind of
well-being research,

00:39:36.870 --> 00:39:38.310
hopefully you wouldn't
find it in this,

00:39:38.310 --> 00:39:40.893
which is a very kind of private
thing with you and your phone.

00:39:40.893 --> 00:39:43.911
It's not someone ringing
you up and asking questions.

00:39:43.911 --> 00:39:45.220
But yeah, it's a good question.

00:39:45.220 --> 00:39:46.920
People have sometimes sort of
expressed surprise at that,

00:39:46.920 --> 00:39:49.350
and sort of said, hmm,
people spending a lot of time

00:39:49.350 --> 00:39:54.390
with their family isn't always
a recipe for high happiness.

00:39:54.390 --> 00:39:56.010
So, yeah, it's a good question.

00:39:58.941 --> 00:40:01.440
AUDIENCE: I mean, I think the
obvious question is are people

00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:02.940
otherwise happier when
they're spending time

00:40:02.940 --> 00:40:03.690
with their family?

00:40:07.199 --> 00:40:08.490
GEORGE MACKERRON: And they are.

00:40:08.490 --> 00:40:10.249
Yeah.

00:40:10.249 --> 00:40:11.790
But I mean, the
things that we looked

00:40:11.790 --> 00:40:13.980
at where happiness was amazing,
that was not controlled.

00:40:13.980 --> 00:40:15.438
That was just sort
of raw averages.

00:40:15.438 --> 00:40:18.300
So you're right that if we
sort of start taking out

00:40:18.300 --> 00:40:20.310
the variation that
we can predict,

00:40:20.310 --> 00:40:22.080
then you will see those peaks
drop almost certainly, right?

00:40:22.080 --> 00:40:23.496
Because they're
with their family.

00:40:23.496 --> 00:40:24.252
They're drinking.

00:40:24.252 --> 00:40:25.710
Probably some of
them are drinking.

00:40:25.710 --> 00:40:27.668
And they're doing other
things that they enjoy.

00:40:27.668 --> 00:40:29.621
And they're not working.

00:40:29.621 --> 00:40:30.120
Yeah.

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:30.840
So some of it's--

00:40:30.840 --> 00:40:32.691
AUDIENCE: --they're not lying.

00:40:32.691 --> 00:40:33.690
GEORGE MACKERRON: Right.

00:40:33.690 --> 00:40:34.050
OK.

00:40:34.050 --> 00:40:35.290
So that's certainly
in line with-- yeah.

00:40:35.290 --> 00:40:35.630
Yeah.

00:40:35.630 --> 00:40:37.880
And I mean, it's an average
effect, so you would need,

00:40:37.880 --> 00:40:40.247
I guess, as long as 2/3
of the people are happier,

00:40:40.247 --> 00:40:41.830
1/3 of the people
could be less happy,

00:40:41.830 --> 00:40:43.980
and the average coefficient
here comes out the way

00:40:43.980 --> 00:40:44.760
that we've seen.

00:40:44.760 --> 00:40:46.260
So there's also
certainly scope here

00:40:46.260 --> 00:40:47.801
for looking more at
the distribution,

00:40:47.801 --> 00:40:49.380
and maybe doing
quantile regression

00:40:49.380 --> 00:40:51.046
and seeing what drives
the low responses

00:40:51.046 --> 00:40:53.044
versus the high responses, say.

00:40:53.044 --> 00:40:54.960
Always in these talks
there's a million things

00:40:54.960 --> 00:40:57.380
that I have to apologize
for not having done.

00:40:57.380 --> 00:40:59.570
There's a lot still to do.

00:40:59.570 --> 00:41:00.591
Yeah.

00:41:00.591 --> 00:41:02.340
AUDIENCE: So with the
fixed effects model,

00:41:02.340 --> 00:41:04.780
you're sort of
looking at differences

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:05.910
within individual people.

00:41:05.910 --> 00:41:09.690
Like they're happier when
they're in a green area.

00:41:09.690 --> 00:41:13.050
But I mean, is
there some concern

00:41:13.050 --> 00:41:16.500
that people might adapt
to these interventions?

00:41:16.500 --> 00:41:18.840
Like maybe the government
puts green spaces everywhere

00:41:18.840 --> 00:41:21.120
and there's still
a big difference,

00:41:21.120 --> 00:41:23.610
but instead of being really
happy in green spaces and just

00:41:23.610 --> 00:41:25.830
kind of meh in city
urban environments,

00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:29.730
now I'm used to green spaces
and urban environments

00:41:29.730 --> 00:41:31.730
are just really terrible?

00:41:31.730 --> 00:41:34.712
AUDIENCE: Or bitter,
because of the difference.

00:41:34.712 --> 00:41:35.670
GEORGE MACKERRON: Yeah.

00:41:35.670 --> 00:41:37.320
And I guess related
to that, there's

00:41:37.320 --> 00:41:39.150
a question of sort of contrasts.

00:41:39.150 --> 00:41:42.110
And so most of our
respondents live in cities.

00:41:42.110 --> 00:41:44.670
And so maybe it's partly that
they're getting out of the city

00:41:44.670 --> 00:41:45.600
and they're going on holiday.

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:47.016
And that's actually
the number one

00:41:47.016 --> 00:41:49.810
question that I wish we'd
asked, is are you on holiday?

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:52.350
And we can kind of
try and get to that

00:41:52.350 --> 00:41:56.310
with various heuristics,
but we don't quite have it.

00:41:56.310 --> 00:41:58.434
So that's an obvious
thing to try and get at,

00:41:58.434 --> 00:42:00.850
also looking at people who
perhaps live in the countryside

00:42:00.850 --> 00:42:02.200
and then visit the city.

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:04.440
That's sort of one of
the top things on my list

00:42:04.440 --> 00:42:07.014
to stop apologizing for
not having done and do.

00:42:07.014 --> 00:42:08.930
And I promised a book
chapter later this year,

00:42:08.930 --> 00:42:12.649
actually, where my plan is to do
that amongst some other things.

00:42:12.649 --> 00:42:14.190
In general in the
happiness research,

00:42:14.190 --> 00:42:16.644
sort of habituation
or adaptation

00:42:16.644 --> 00:42:17.560
is certainly an issue.

00:42:17.560 --> 00:42:18.976
And I mean, one
of the things that

00:42:18.976 --> 00:42:21.957
drove me to do this was I moved
down to London to do the PhD.

00:42:21.957 --> 00:42:23.790
I was previously in
Cambridge at that point.

00:42:23.790 --> 00:42:25.456
And Cambridge was
green and quite clean.

00:42:25.456 --> 00:42:28.140
And London was incredibly
kind of dirty and polluted.

00:42:28.140 --> 00:42:29.490
And that kind of got me down.

00:42:29.490 --> 00:42:32.050
By the end of five,
six years in London,

00:42:32.050 --> 00:42:33.750
I was getting-- at
least, I was aware

00:42:33.750 --> 00:42:36.630
of it getting me down less.

00:42:36.630 --> 00:42:37.890
So no, that is a question.

00:42:37.890 --> 00:42:40.290
And that is certainly a
question for policymakers.

00:42:40.290 --> 00:42:41.250
You know, there's all
kinds of other things

00:42:41.250 --> 00:42:42.090
people adapt to as well.

00:42:42.090 --> 00:42:44.460
You know, they adapt to sort
of chronic health problems

00:42:44.460 --> 00:42:46.080
that the government
thinks it's worth spending

00:42:46.080 --> 00:42:47.350
quite a lot of money to avoid.

00:42:47.350 --> 00:42:49.830
Those then don't seem to
affect people's happiness

00:42:49.830 --> 00:42:54.306
in the very long run as
much as you'd expect.

00:42:54.306 --> 00:42:55.680
One of the reasons
for that might

00:42:55.680 --> 00:42:56.970
be that happiness
isn't the only thing

00:42:56.970 --> 00:42:58.219
that people are interested in.

00:42:58.219 --> 00:42:59.710
And in fact, the
football research

00:42:59.710 --> 00:43:01.710
also talks to that idea
that happiness might not

00:43:01.710 --> 00:43:03.060
be the only thing that
people are interested in.

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:05.790
Because unless everyone
supports teams that always win,

00:43:05.790 --> 00:43:07.400
which I'm pretty
sure isn't true,

00:43:07.400 --> 00:43:09.720
then losses are so
much more painful

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:12.480
than wins are pleasant that
you'd think that they weren't

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:15.840
maximizing the sort of the
integral of their happiness

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:18.450
by going to football
matches and following them.

00:43:18.450 --> 00:43:22.440
So that's a bit of a rambling
answer, but it kind of-- yeah.

00:43:22.440 --> 00:43:26.130
Your point is still
valid and interesting.

00:43:26.130 --> 00:43:27.672
What you'd, I
guess, like to do is

00:43:27.672 --> 00:43:29.130
have some kind of,
again, some kind

00:43:29.130 --> 00:43:31.620
of trial, some kind of random
assignment of more or less

00:43:31.620 --> 00:43:32.670
green space.

00:43:32.670 --> 00:43:35.300
See what happens if a park
ends up being closed for a year

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:37.439
to the people who
live nearby, say.

00:43:37.439 --> 00:43:39.480
And then you might look
at the profile over time.

00:43:39.480 --> 00:43:41.850
If there is some adaptation,
how much is there?

00:43:41.850 --> 00:43:43.740
I suspect that it
wouldn't be complete.

00:43:43.740 --> 00:43:45.450
There are lots of
other things that--

00:43:45.450 --> 00:43:47.889
the reasons that we think
people like green spaces,

00:43:47.889 --> 00:43:49.680
you would imagine
perhaps wouldn't go away.

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:50.550
So you know, there's
an opportunity

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:52.720
for sort of physical exercise
that improves health.

00:43:52.720 --> 00:43:54.910
There's an opportunity for
socializing with people.

00:43:54.910 --> 00:43:57.740
And there's also this idea
that we evolved in the savanna,

00:43:57.740 --> 00:43:59.790
or on the edge of
forests, or wherever

00:43:59.790 --> 00:44:02.041
it is that we evolved over
tens of thousands of years.

00:44:02.041 --> 00:44:04.165
It might well be something
that just kind of causes

00:44:04.165 --> 00:44:06.936
us to find these patterns in
our visual system and kind

00:44:06.936 --> 00:44:08.310
of attractive,
You this biophilia

00:44:08.310 --> 00:44:10.050
hypothesis of Eo Wilson.

00:44:10.050 --> 00:44:11.697
So I would be surprised
if all of those

00:44:11.697 --> 00:44:12.780
were totally adapted away.

00:44:12.780 --> 00:44:14.821
But it would certainly be
interesting to find out

00:44:14.821 --> 00:44:15.575
how far they were.

00:44:15.575 --> 00:44:17.700
AUDIENCE: There's a new
park in East London, right,

00:44:17.700 --> 00:44:20.100
during the time period
that you studied?

00:44:20.100 --> 00:44:22.130
GEORGE MACKERRON:
Yeah, the Olympic Park.

00:44:22.130 --> 00:44:23.338
Yeah, we should look at that.

00:44:23.338 --> 00:44:24.995
We have briefly looked
at the Olympics,

00:44:24.995 --> 00:44:27.620
mainly with the ax to grind that
I wonder if it would have been

00:44:27.620 --> 00:44:29.953
an awful lot cheaper just to
have a couple of extra bank

00:44:29.953 --> 00:44:31.380
holidays.

00:44:31.380 --> 00:44:32.630
Might not turn out to be true.

00:44:32.630 --> 00:44:34.380
I haven't really checked
in enough detail.

00:44:34.380 --> 00:44:36.385
I suspect that we don't
have enough responses

00:44:36.385 --> 00:44:37.010
from that time.

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:38.480
And there aren't enough
people living around it.

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:39.730
Because they're also
kind of building-- well,

00:44:39.730 --> 00:44:41.810
I guess the houses have just
been built, haven't they?

00:44:41.810 --> 00:44:44.450
People have presumably all just
kind of moved there as well,

00:44:44.450 --> 00:44:46.490
because it was a sort
of big redevelopment.

00:44:46.490 --> 00:44:47.656
It's an interesting thought.

00:44:47.656 --> 00:44:49.250
It's the right kind
of thing, I think,

00:44:49.250 --> 00:44:50.640
for us to think
about looking it.

00:44:50.640 --> 00:44:52.227
Yeah.

00:44:52.227 --> 00:44:53.060
AUDIENCE: Hi, sorry.

00:44:53.060 --> 00:44:56.042
You had sports and doing sports
as one of the top things that

00:44:56.042 --> 00:44:56.750
drives happiness.

00:44:56.750 --> 00:44:59.157
But also drinking alcohol,
as well, was on that list.

00:44:59.157 --> 00:45:01.490
Just wondering about the trade
off between like virtuous

00:45:01.490 --> 00:45:04.550
behaviors and then
maybe not so virtuous

00:45:04.550 --> 00:45:09.104
behaviors and how
they impact happiness.

00:45:09.104 --> 00:45:11.270
GEORGE MACKERRON: Yeah, I'm
not sure I have anything

00:45:11.270 --> 00:45:13.160
very intelligent to say about
that, apart from that, yes,

00:45:13.160 --> 00:45:14.270
it does sound interesting.

00:45:14.270 --> 00:45:16.460
And I suppose if
we've got people

00:45:16.460 --> 00:45:19.749
that we observe over
a long period of time,

00:45:19.749 --> 00:45:21.290
then we could
potentially, I suppose,

00:45:21.290 --> 00:45:23.206
look at that kind of
cumulative effect of what

00:45:23.206 --> 00:45:23.957
you've been doing.

00:45:23.957 --> 00:45:26.540
I mean, one of the things that
actually I don't do at all here

00:45:26.540 --> 00:45:28.081
is you don't have
any dynamic models.

00:45:28.081 --> 00:45:30.037
So we kind of account
for the responses

00:45:30.037 --> 00:45:31.620
being from the same
people in the era.

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:33.830
But we don't use the fact
that we could kind of,

00:45:33.830 --> 00:45:36.492
this next response follows
the previous response.

00:45:36.492 --> 00:45:38.200
And so, in general,
we could kind of both

00:45:38.200 --> 00:45:39.616
do that on a kind
of shorter level

00:45:39.616 --> 00:45:41.117
and I guess also
on a longer level,

00:45:41.117 --> 00:45:42.950
and see people who often
report that they're

00:45:42.950 --> 00:45:45.241
doing sport versus people
who often report that they're

00:45:45.241 --> 00:45:46.335
drinking, for example.

00:45:46.335 --> 00:45:48.710
Some of these things, certainly
the drinking, potentially

00:45:48.710 --> 00:45:49.880
has reverse
causality, because it

00:45:49.880 --> 00:45:52.046
might be that people drink
because they're stressed.

00:45:52.046 --> 00:45:54.427
And it can be awkward, but
with the time series data,

00:45:54.427 --> 00:45:56.510
we might have a chance of
addressing some of that,

00:45:56.510 --> 00:45:58.135
because you can see
what precedes what.

