00:48:00.706 --> 00:48:02.330
Are there any
differences between these

00:48:02.330 --> 00:48:04.281
prompted and self-reported?

00:48:04.281 --> 00:48:05.780
GEORGE MACKERRON:
So mostly, I mean,

00:48:05.780 --> 00:48:07.820
there's an advantage in letting
people do it at any time, which

00:48:07.820 --> 00:48:09.200
is that they feel like
they're in control,

00:48:09.200 --> 00:48:10.991
and they can also sort
of show it to people

00:48:10.991 --> 00:48:13.220
and show them how it works.

00:48:13.220 --> 00:48:14.610
It's a good question.

00:48:14.610 --> 00:48:15.490
It's not something
I've focused on.

00:48:15.490 --> 00:48:17.270
So generally, we've
just taken the responses

00:48:17.270 --> 00:48:19.250
that were prompted, because
the idea of this experience

00:48:19.250 --> 00:48:21.020
sampling method is you
want a kind of probability

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:22.853
sample of all the moments
in someone's life.

00:48:22.853 --> 00:48:25.294
And of course, they
may have reasons.

00:48:25.294 --> 00:48:26.710
They may be showing
it to someone,

00:48:26.710 --> 00:48:28.876
or they may be doing it
because they're particularly

00:48:28.876 --> 00:48:30.170
happy or particularly unhappy.

00:48:30.170 --> 00:48:32.510
So I suspect that you're
right, they would be different.

00:48:32.510 --> 00:48:35.304
I guess I'm not 100% sure what
the difference would tell us,

00:48:35.304 --> 00:48:37.220
but it would be a thing
that we could look at.

00:48:37.220 --> 00:48:38.970
Generally we can take
a response, I think,

00:48:38.970 --> 00:48:42.170
that's within an hour of
having being signaled.

00:48:42.170 --> 00:48:46.610
And about half of signals get
a response within an hour.

00:48:46.610 --> 00:48:48.450
You can reduce that or
increase it, I think.

00:48:48.450 --> 00:48:51.957
And in ESM work, typically, it's
sometimes been just 20 minutes.

00:48:51.957 --> 00:48:53.540
But then in ESM work,
typically people

00:48:53.540 --> 00:48:54.956
have made up half
their responses.

00:48:54.956 --> 00:48:56.797
So it's kind of swings
and roundabouts.

00:48:56.797 --> 00:48:58.880
It doesn't make a lot of
difference to the effects

00:48:58.880 --> 00:49:00.588
that we were looking
at here, whether you

00:49:00.588 --> 00:49:03.140
take a really short window or
a really long window, which

00:49:03.140 --> 00:49:04.172
is encouraging.

00:49:04.172 --> 00:49:06.380
Of course, we are missing
half of people's responses.

00:49:06.380 --> 00:49:08.030
And in fact, the
original Mappiness

00:49:08.030 --> 00:49:10.410
requires a data
connection to beep you.

00:49:10.410 --> 00:49:12.770
It was push notifications,
because local notifications

00:49:12.770 --> 00:49:13.580
weren't available.

00:49:13.580 --> 00:49:15.590
Which is a shame, because people
up in the middle of nowhere up

00:49:15.590 --> 00:49:17.210
a mountain might
be the happiest,

00:49:17.210 --> 00:49:19.806
but we can't ding them.

00:49:19.806 --> 00:49:21.227
But yeah.

00:49:21.227 --> 00:49:23.060
AUDIENCE: Have you seen
anything interesting

00:49:23.060 --> 00:49:26.070
as people have aged
through your study?

00:49:31.756 --> 00:49:32.630
GEORGE MACKERRON: No.

00:49:38.230 --> 00:49:41.244
I guess we could try that.

00:49:41.244 --> 00:49:43.660
It would be difficult, though,
I suppose, to disentangle--

00:49:43.660 --> 00:49:45.493
I don't know if we've
got a long enough time

00:49:45.493 --> 00:49:47.890
series to disentangle you
aging versus the world going up

00:49:47.890 --> 00:49:49.970
in flames.

00:49:49.970 --> 00:49:54.340
And I mean, in general,
we'd expect a big U shape.

00:49:54.340 --> 00:49:56.610
So in the subjective well-being
literature generally,

00:49:56.610 --> 00:49:58.720
there's this kind of
big U, where being 40,

00:49:58.720 --> 00:50:01.690
45 is the worst.

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:03.015
And then it picks up again.

00:50:03.015 --> 00:50:04.585
And some of it
picking up again is

00:50:04.585 --> 00:50:07.870
that, again, people retire, and
they're not working anymore.

00:50:07.870 --> 00:50:09.500
But that's what
we expect to find.

00:50:09.500 --> 00:50:11.250
But I haven't looked
at that in Mappiness.

00:50:11.250 --> 00:50:13.708
As I say, I'm not sure if we've
got the best data for that.

00:50:17.002 --> 00:50:18.960
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
some of these scenarios

00:50:18.960 --> 00:50:21.512
where there's a
lot of variability

00:50:21.512 --> 00:50:23.220
in terms of happiness
for a single event,

00:50:23.220 --> 00:50:24.590
for example having children.

00:50:24.590 --> 00:50:28.140
Are there things that are
much more consistent, and then

00:50:28.140 --> 00:50:30.900
so maybe the government
could do or companies

00:50:30.900 --> 00:50:32.560
could do to improve?

00:50:32.560 --> 00:50:34.920
Are there things that
everyone agreed on

00:50:34.920 --> 00:50:35.850
as being happy things?

00:50:40.399 --> 00:50:42.690
GEORGE MACKERRON: I mean,
one of the interesting things

00:50:42.690 --> 00:50:44.648
in relation to economists
normally saying, just

00:50:44.648 --> 00:50:46.770
get richer, versus
us thinking are there

00:50:46.770 --> 00:50:48.770
unintended consequences
of getting richer?

00:50:48.770 --> 00:50:50.190
I mean, certainly one of the
things that springs to mind

00:50:50.190 --> 00:50:52.920
is sort of people in city jobs
who get paid vast salaries

00:50:52.920 --> 00:50:56.560
but don't have any option at
all except to work full time

00:50:56.560 --> 00:50:58.480
or double full time.

00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:00.904
I kind of think that
working time regulations are

00:51:00.904 --> 00:51:02.070
potentially quite promising.

00:51:02.070 --> 00:51:05.290
Now, you know, if you could have
people cut their working hours,

00:51:05.290 --> 00:51:08.370
but not have it be a signal
that they weren't committed,

00:51:08.370 --> 00:51:11.590
they might do well with four
days instead of five days

00:51:11.590 --> 00:51:15.620
and 80% of their salary, say.

00:51:15.620 --> 00:51:17.336
The Economics Foundation
have quite a lot

00:51:17.336 --> 00:51:18.960
of interesting work about
that, and that potentially

00:51:18.960 --> 00:51:20.730
is also kind of good for the
environment, because, you know,

00:51:20.730 --> 00:51:24.000
your city lawyer only has a sort
of one weekend in every four

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:26.035
off, and then jets far
away and comes back.

00:51:26.035 --> 00:51:27.660
Probably isn't made
very happy by that,

00:51:27.660 --> 00:51:30.034
and in addition, they're kind
of using a lot of the world

00:51:30.034 --> 00:51:32.640
resources to do it.

00:51:32.640 --> 00:51:36.860
Work life balance
issues, potentially.

00:51:36.860 --> 00:51:40.710
Yeah, I don't have a
brilliant answer to that.

00:51:40.710 --> 00:51:42.210
I mean, redistribution,
potentially.

00:51:42.210 --> 00:51:44.610
I showed you this chart
about how little difference

00:51:44.610 --> 00:51:46.810
it makes kind of up at
the top end of income,

00:51:46.810 --> 00:51:48.600
how much more income you get
compared to how much difference

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:49.730
it makes at the bottom.

00:51:49.730 --> 00:51:51.986
And economists are normally
very worried about that.

00:51:51.986 --> 00:51:53.610
They're like these
Pareto improvements,

00:51:53.610 --> 00:51:54.930
right, where everyone
can agree that if you

00:51:54.930 --> 00:51:57.210
can make some people happier
and no one less happy,

00:51:57.210 --> 00:51:58.730
then that's great.

00:51:58.730 --> 00:52:01.230
But they generally kind of don't
like to talk about the ones

00:52:01.230 --> 00:52:02.605
where you make
someone a tiny bit

00:52:02.605 --> 00:52:05.309
less happy to make
someone else much happier.

00:52:05.309 --> 00:52:07.350
And you know, that's a
difficult political thing.

00:52:07.350 --> 00:52:11.440
But that's some of what
politics is about, I suppose.

00:52:11.440 --> 00:52:13.154
So there's a thought.

00:52:13.154 --> 00:52:14.820
Actually, this is
both my Twitter handle

00:52:14.820 --> 00:52:15.640
and GitHub handle.

00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:17.473
And probably not worth
going to the Twitter,

00:52:17.473 --> 00:52:20.581
because it's just
political ranting.

